SIMPLE: inflect
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Inflect
<hw>In*flect"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Inflected</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Inflecting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>inflectere</ets>,
<ets>inflexum</ets>; pref. <ets>in-</ets> in + <ets>flectere</ets> to
bend. See <er>Flexible</er>, and cf. <er>Inflex</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To turn from a direct line or course; to bend; to incline, to
deflect; to curve; to bow.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Are they [the rays of the sun] not reflected, refracted, and
<qex>inflected</qex> by one and the same principle ?</q> <rj><qau>Sir I.
Newton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Gram.)</fld> <def>To vary, as a noun or a verb in
its terminations; to decline, as a noun or adjective, or to conjugate,
as a verb.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To modulate, as the voice.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Inflected</ent>⟦br⟧
